<F P=100> GERMANY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Token Strike Called for 20,000 Engineering Workers </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0802145194 Berlin DDP/ADN in German 1057 GMT 8 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0802145194 </F>
<F P=104>  Berlin DDP/ADN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Munich (DDP/ADN) -- Following the failure of pay 
talks in Cologne for the engineering industry, IG Metall has 
called around 20,000 workers in over 30 factories in Bavaria out 
on token strike. According to the Bavarian region of the union, 
those affected include the car manufacturer Audi in Ingolstadt 
and Bosch in Bamberg, as well as Siemens and Siemens-Nixdorf 
plants in Upper Bavaria. Rallies and demonstrations are planned 
outside the workplace in Ingolstadt, Waldkraiburg, and Bamberg. 
Among the factories affected by the token strikes is the 
Zeuna-Staerker firm of Hubert Staerker, the president of the 
Bavarian Engineering Association, in Augsburg. 

</TEXT>

