<F P=100> SPAIN </F>
<H3> <TI>   Madrid Wants `Firm Decision' on Sarajevo </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0702144694 Madrid RNE-1 Radio Network in Spanish 1300 GMT 
7 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0702144694 </F>
<F P=104>  Madrid RNE-1 Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report from Brussels by correspondent Nacho Hernandez] </F>
  [Excerpt] [Hernandez] For the Spanish authorities there 
must be a warning to the Serbs so that they will lift the siege 
of Sarajevo. For Foreign Minister Javier Solana the solution to 
the conflict in Bosnia is not military, although he has faith in 
the deterrent effects of a decision within NATO. 
  [Begin Solana recording] So that those responsible for the 
massacres of the last few days will receive an unequivocal 
signal from the Atlantic alliance of its readiness to raise the 
siege of Sarajevo. And I believe I can tell you that I believe 
there will be a sufficient consensus today within the Atlantic 
alliance and within the European Union for a clear, firm 
decision to be taken with regard to Sarajevo. [end recording] 
  [Hernandez] A formula could be sought for Sarajevo to be 
defined as a UN-protected zone. The foreign minister confirmed 
that there are measures to protect the troops, relocating them 
according to the proximity of the danger -- we mean the UNPROFOR 
[UN Protection Forces] forces which are now carrying out 
humanitarian aid work in Yugoslavia. We must cooperate, the 
foreign minister said, to end the siege of Sarajevo. In his 
opinion there is a sufficient consensus to make a decision and 
give a forceful response. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

