<F P=100> SPAIN </F>
<H3> <TI>   Minister Expresses `Skepticism' on Bosnian Air Strikes </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0802202094 Madrid RNE-1 Radio Network in Spanish 1900 GMT 
8 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0802202094 </F>
<F P=104>  Madrid RNE-1 Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Spanish Defense Minister Julian Garcia Vargas 
expressed his skepticism about the efficiency of possible air 
strikes on Serb positions in ending the Bosnian conflict. Garcia 
Vargas says he understands the need for firm action on the 
international community's behalf because of the very serious 
situation in Sarajevo. However, the minister admits that for 
various military and technical reasons a possible NATO air 
strike will not be enough to lift the siege of the city. 
  [Begin Garcia Vargas recording] There is a request 
formulated 
by the international community asking for the siege to be 
lifted. The possibility exists that force may be used in a very 
selective and specific way. That is to say that lifting the 
siege without deploying ground forces would be very difficult. 
Why? Because the mortar sites cannot be attacked from the air, 
the planes cannot see them from the air. So, air strikes would 
be a warning and an expression of the international community's 
will to put pressure on the areas that right now have the most 
responsibility in the conflict, and specially on those who are 
carrying out these unacceptable massacres in the city of 
Sarajevo. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

