<F P=100> CYPRUS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government To Raise Issues at Proximity Talks </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC0802222794 Nicosia I SIMERINI in Greek 8 Feb 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> NC0802222794 </F>
<F P=104>  Nicosia I SIMERINI </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Greek </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Kostas Venizelos] </F>
  [Text] The Cypriot Government has prepared a list of issues 
and questions to discuss at the proximity talks. The list 
includes issues of security and legal aspects that may create 
danger from the pseudostate's direct or indirect recognition. 
The United Nations has also submitted a list of issues in 
preparing the agenda for the talks that will begin late next 
week. 
  According to reliable I SIMERINI information, the government 
will raise the following issues and questions: 
  First: The simultaneous opening of Varosha and Nicosia 
Airport. The president will set a period of 18 months for the 
implementation of these measures. 
  Second: There must be no occupation army around the 
Famagusta 
fenced-off area. This falls under the "security" aspect. 
  Third: Access to the fenced-off area must be possible from 
the free areas. The Greek side wants a road through Dherinia 
but there is also talk of a passage through the British bases 
(in Ayios Nikolaos). This is also a security issue. 
  Fourth: The issue of travel documents. The passports that 
the Turkish Cypriots will use when traveling from Nicosia 
Airport and how they will be stamped. 
  Fifth: Who will have control of the sea area around Varosha? 
  Sixth: How will the Cypriot Government transfer control of 
Nicosia Airport to the United Nations? 
  Seventh: The Cypriot Government will not pay even one cent 
to 
repair the airport and Famagusta's neighborhoods that will be 
placed under UN control. 
  The United Nations yesterday submitted their own list of 
issues. Gustave Feissel, the UN secretary general's alternate 
special representative in Cyprus, and UN Political Adviser John 
Paul Kavanagh yesterday met President Glavkos Kliridhis and 
Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktas. The key points, as they 
have described them, concern security issues raised by both 
sides, access to the fenced-off area, movement from and to 
Varosha, passports, stamps, authorities and how they will be 
transferred to the United Nations, who will have the right to 
land and take off at the airport (Turkish Cypriot Airlines), and 
timetables. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-38909 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drweu027_o_94007" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-WEU-94-027 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  9 Feb 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> CYPRUS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Clark, UN Experts Expected To Arrive 12 Feb </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC0802123994 Nicosia Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation Radio 
Network in Greek 1130 GMT 8 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC0802123994 </F>
<F P=104>  Nicosia Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation Radio 
Network </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Greek </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] A reliable source today said that proximity talks on 
the confidence-building measures [CBM'S] based on the three 
documents submitted by the UN secretary general to the two sides 
will begin in Nicosia on 17 February. The source added that Joe 
Clark, the UN secretary general's special representative in 
Cyprus, is expected in Cyprus on Saturday [12 February] 
accompanied by a group of UN experts. The same source clarified 
that it is not the same group of experts who visited Cyprus 
earlier and prepared reports on the fenced-off area of Famagusta 
and the Nicosia International Airport. 
  Referring to the UN secretary general's two-month deadline 
for the Nicosia-New York talks to conclude, government spokesman 
Ioannis Kasoulidhis said the government believes this is the 
maximum period that should be allocated, adding: Discussion on 
the substance of the Cyprus issue should begin immediately 
afterward. 
  The spokesman said that negotiations are now being held with 
the UN secretary general's representatives to prepare a list of 
points described as key positions--the answers to questions such 
as how the Nicosia Airport will operate and how the fenced-off 
area of Famagusta will be opened up. Kasoulidhis added that 
this list will remain open until late next week for suggestions 
to be added by both sides. 
  Answering another question, the spokesman said the National 
Council members will have the opportunity to express their 
positions on the points in the list before it is finalized. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-38910 </DOCNO>
