<F P=100> GREECE </F>
<H3> <TI>   Leaders Comment on EU Communique on Bosnia </TI></H3>
<H4>   Spokesman: Does Not Contradict Policy </H4>
<F P=102> NC0802140094 Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network in 
Greek 1230 GMT 8 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC0802140094 </F>
<F P=104>  Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Greek </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpts] Asked how he explains the government's double 
talk on Bosnia-Herzegovina, government spokesman Evangelos 
Venizelos said the communique issued by the European Union [EU] 
Council of Ministers, which conferred in Brussels yesterday, 
does not contradict Greek positions. He said the firm Greek 
view--not just the government's--that Balkan countries should 
not get involved in any war remains firm. He added that Foreign 
Minister Karolos Papoulias' handling of things was calm and 
responsible. [passage omitted] 
  Asked whether the Greek presidency contacted the Serb 
leadership immediately after the EU foreign ministers communique 
was issued, Venizelos said Greece has the capability to contact 
and pressure all sides for a solution. He added: This 
capability is not limited to Serbia. 

</TEXT>

