<F P=100> TURKEY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ciller Message to Clinton, Mitterand, Kohl on Bosnia </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  TA0802151594 Ankara ANATOLIA in English 1445 GMT 8 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> TA0802151594 </F>
<F P=104>  Ankara ANATOLIA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Ankara, Feb 8 (A.A) -- Premier Tansu Ciller on 
Tuesday [8 February] sent a message to the U.S. President Bill 
Clinton, French President Francois Mitterand, German Chancellor 
Helmut Kohl, and British Prime Minister John Major on the 
conflict in Bosnia-Herzegovina. 
  Ciller in the message conveyed her impressions to the 
leaders 
she viewed during her visit to Bosnia on Feb 2 saying "the 
developments in Bosnia up to now showed that the aggressor was 
allowed to gain territory by force." 
  The message went on saying "the aggressive powers continue 
their actions to devastate the multi-cultural structure of 
Bosnia and a mortar attack of Serbians which killed 68 people 
and wounded 200 others targeted the Bosnian civilians. She 
added that the attack was a challenge to all civilization values 
and initiatives for a peaceful solution. 
  Ciller described the recent letter of the UN General 
Secretary Butrus Butrus-Ghali sent to NATO which called for an 
air operation and protection of Sarajevo against Serbian attacks 
as "late but favorable." 
  Ciller said such an air operation will protect Sarajevo from 
Serbian attacks and will give an open message to the aggressors. 
  She said if NATO fails to take necessary measures after this 
letter, it will lose its credibility. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

