<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Sentiment Growing in NATO for Ultimatum to Serbs </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0902090794 Paris AFP in English 0849 GMT 9 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU0902090794 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By Peter Mackler] </F>
  [Text] Brussels, Feb 9 (AFP) -- NATO sought Wednesday [9 
February] to reach a consensus on airstrikes against the Bosnian 
Serbs, with sentiment growing for giving them a warning to 
withdraw their artillery from Sarajevo, alliance sources said. 
  A NATO source said "a majority, not everybody" in the 
16-member alliance was in favour of putting the Serbs on notice 
following the mortar attack last weekend that killed 68 people 
in Sarajevo's central market. 
  But NATO requires unanimity to take a decision and Greece 
has 
come out strongly against the airstrikes. Canada has also 
expressed strong reservations for fear of reprisals against its 
troops serving in Bosnia. 
  In Washington a U.S. official said the United States would 
ask its NATO allies to authorize bombing raids against the 
Bosnian Serbs unless they pulled their heavy weapons back from 
the hills around Sarajevo. 
  The NATO source said two proposals were on the table at a 
meeting of NATO ambassadors here, one by the United States and 
France and the other by Britain. Both contained the notion of a 
warning but avoided the word ultimatum. 
  The aim would be to give the Serbs seven to 10 days to 
withdraw their heavy weapons at least 20 kilometers (13 miles) 
from the predominantly Moslem Bosnian capital. The Bosnian 
army's artillery would be put under international control. 
  The source expressed optimism for reaching a consensus. 
"Last 
night we were closing together," he said. 
  The alliance was to consider a request by UN Secretary 
General Butrus Butrus-Ghali to authorise the use of its 
warplanes for a punitive action to deter future attacks such as 
Saturday's slaughter in Sarejevo's market. 
  But NATO, stung to action by the worst incident in the 
22-month-old conflict, appeared to have a broader purpose in 
mind: lifting the siege of Sarajevo immediately as urged Monday 
by the European Community. 
  In Washington Secretary of State Warren Christopher 
emphasised that the military threat was paired with a vow to 
step up pressure on Bosnia's three warring factions to reach a 
political settlement. 
  Christopher said the military and diplomatic initiatives 
were 
"very closely interrelated. They are interlocked. One does not 
take the place of the other. They go together." 
  Clinton approved the twin-pronged response to the grizzling 
[as received] shelling of Sarajevo's market on Tuesday. 
  During the day he talked by telephone to French President 
Francois Mitterrand, French sources said, but declined to give 
details. 
  Clinton also telephoned Canadian Prime Minister Jean 
Chretien, and tried but failed to contact British Prime Minister 
John Major, said a senior administration official who asked not 
to be identified. 
  Canada and Britain, the largest contributors to the UN 
Protection Force in Bosnia after France -- which has deployed 
6,000 blue helmets, are reluctant to back Paris' call for an air 
strike, fearing it might expose their own troops to Serbian 
retaliation. 
  Washington hopes to find "an agreeable position" with Paris 
on a minor sticking point relating to the distance to which the 
Serbian artillery should pull back from Sarajevo, the senior 
administration official said. 
  But as far as an agreement within NATO in the Brussels 
meeting, "I don't know if this will happen tomorrow," he added. 
  The U.S. Chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, John 
Shalikashvili, warned a Senate committee on Tuesday that air 
power was limited. 
  "Air power alone can not bump someone into a peace treaty," 
he said. 
  He said NATO's North Atlantic Council would discuss "whether 
you can use limited air power not to stop, but to reduce, the 
chance of a tragedy that occurred in Sarajevo the other day." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

