<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Canada Still Opposed to Air Strikes in Bosnia </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0802152294 Montreal Radio Canada International in English 
1430 GMT 8 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0802152294 </F>
<F P=104>  Montreal Radio Canada International </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpt] [passage omitted] Defense Minister David 
Collenette says that despite the horror of the mortar attack on 
Sarajevo the Canadian Government is still opposed to air strikes. 
  [Begin Collenette recording] We haven't changed our position 
since the prime minister announced it last month, which was that 
we believe that air strikes were not the way to deal with the 
problem at this time, until all other courses of action fail. 
As Mr. Ouellet said yesterday, we still believe that a 
negotiated settlement can be arrived at. [end recording] 
  Defense Minister David Collenette: A primary consideration 
for Ottawa is the safety of Canada's 2,400 peacekeepers in 
former Yugoslavia. 

</TEXT>

