<F P=100> CYPRUS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government To Discuss CBM's Implementation </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC0802141794 Nicosia Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation Radio 
Network in Greek 1130 GMT 8 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC0802141794 </F>
<F P=104>  Nicosia Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation Radio 
Network </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Greek </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Foreign Minister Alekos Mikhailidhis said the 
government is not prepared to discuss any changes to the 
provisions in the confidence-building measures [CBM's] for the 
return of the entire fenced-off area of Famagusta. Speaking 
after a meeting with the Famagusta mayor and municipal 
counselors, Mikhailidhis said the government is not discussing 
the contents of the measures package, but its implementation. 
He added: These measures very clearly refer to Famagusta's 
fenced-off area. 
  Asked about the safety of Famagusta's residents, 
Mikhailidhis 
said this is one issue that will be discussed. He said: We 
want enough security so that whoever returns to Famagusta will 
feel that they are returning to their homes permanently. 
Mikhailidhis said the implementation of the CBM's would allow 
15,000-16,000 residents to return to Famagusta. 
  Famagusta Mayor Andreas Pouyiouros said the citizens of 
Famagusta number 60,000, adding that the Municipal Council's 
position is that the whole town should be returned in accordance 
with UN Security Council Resolution 550. Pouyiouros described a 
UN experts' report on the implementation of the CBM's as 
unacceptable and intolerable, adding that the world's powers and 
the United Nations see the measures as the first step toward an 
overall Cyprus solution. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

