<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   NATO Participants Comment on Bosnia Declaration, Air Strikes </TI></H3>
<H4>   FRG Welcomes NATO Decision </H4>
<F P=102> LD1002103294 Berlin DDP/ADN in German 0957 GMT 10 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1002103294 </F>
<F P=104>  Berlin DDP/ADN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Bonn (DDP/ADN) -- The German Government welcomes the 
NATO decision to impose an ultimatum on the attackers in 
Sarajevo, giving them 10 days to withdraw their heavy weapons 
outside a radius of 20 km around Sarajevo. Otherwise, NATO is 
threatening to destroy Serb positions with air strikes. Federal 
Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel told the press in Bonn today that 
everything must be done to end any further bloodshed: "There has 
to be an end to the siege of Sarajevo." 
  Kinkel spoke of "decisions with very far-reaching 
implications." However, a political solution still has priority 
over a military one, he said. NATO hopes that there will be no 
need to implement the decision it has made. A peaceful solution 
cannot, however, be achieved against the wishes of the three 
warring parties -- the Moslems, Serbs, and Croats. He therefore 
appealed urgently to the three warring parties to do their 
utmost for a peaceful solution. 

</TEXT>

