<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   NATO Participants Comment on Bosnia Declaration, Air Strikes </TI></H3>
<H4>   Greece To Refuse Use of NATO Base in Aktion </H4>
<F P=102> NC0902132594 Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network in 
Greek 1230 GMT 9 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC0902132594 </F>
<F P=104>  Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Greek </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Asked what Greece would do if the permanent NATO 
members today decided to use force in Bosnia-Herzegovina, 
government spokesman Evangelos Venizelos said: We will not 
allow the NATO base in Aktion to be used, we will withdraw the 
Greek crew members from the AWACS [Airborne Warning And Control 
System], and demand that no Balkan country participates in 
military operations in the former Yugoslavia. Venizelos 
stressed that this is the unanimous view of all political party 
leaders; it was expressed at a meeting under President 
Konstandinos Karamanlis on 10 May 1993. 
  Venizelos added: These positions are firm and our permanent 
representative Ambassador Zafiropoulos will convey them to NATO. 
We hope that a diplomatic solution to end this bloody war will 
be found, that is, an immediate and viable solution. 
  Answering another question, Venizelos said Greece is not 
willing to veto a decision on military operations because, as he 
explained, the international common view would see Greece as 
part of the Yugoslav crisis. The spokesman concluded: On the 
contrary, the international community should realize that our 
country is a factor of stability in the Balkans. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

