<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   `Violent Methods' `Illogical' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC1002070894 Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network in 
Greek 0500 GMT 10 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC1002070894 </F>
<F P=104>  Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Greek </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by correspondent Nikolaos Bellos from Brussels] </F>
  [Excerpt] [Passage omitted] According to reliable NATO 
sources, Greece and Canada were expressing opposition to air 
raids until the last minute. The decision was unanimous, but 
the Greek permanent representative, Ambassador Vasilios 
Zafiropoulos, submitted the following statement to the Council's 
minutes: 
  The Greek presidency stresses that in view of the latest 
developments--the decision of the Serbs and Muslims to withdraw 
their heavy weapons--and based on information supplied by 
international mediators Lord Owen and Thorvald Stoltenberg on 
Sarajevo's demilitarization, it believes that pursuing the same 
goal through violent methods is not only illogical but also 
unavoidably creates the danger of a negative outcome. 
Therefore, in addition to expressing general reservations about 
the purpose of air raids, the Greek Presidency separates 
[dhiakhorizi] its position. 

</TEXT>

