<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Bonn Favors `Tougher Position' Toward Bosnian Serbs </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0902123994 Hamburg DPA in German 1139 GMT 9 Feb 94--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU0902123994 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Bonn -- As a result of the massacre in Sarajevo, 
the Chancellor's Office is advocating a clearly tougher position 
but not necessarily air strikes. Shortly before the meeting of 
the NATO Council in Brussels today, senior officials hoped for 
the full implementation of UN Resolution 836, which asked NATO 
to establish protection zones. According to the officials, this 
also includes protection of convoys transporting humanitarian 
aid, which has not been guaranteed so far. 
  Officials believe this would also mean clearing the path for 
the convoys by forcibly removing blockades. Combat helicopters 
might be used for this purpose ("close air support"). Unlike 
air strikes, these measures would be covered by the existing 
mandate and would not require a new Security Council resolution, 
which would be difficult to achieve at the moment in view of the 
negative attitude of Russia and other permanent members. 
  According to the Chancellor's Office, the full utilization 
of 
the existing mandate would improve the credibility of the West, 
and a higher deterrence effect would be achieved. Public 
demands for large-scale air strikes, recently voiced on 
television by Bernd Schmidbauer, the minister in the 
Chancellor's Office, who is responsible for the intelligence 
services, have met with great reservations. Schmidbauer's view 
is not shared by others at the Chancellor's Office, it has 
become known. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

