<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kohl, Kinkel Comment on Bosnian Crisis </TI></H3>
<H4>   Kohl Supports U.S. Position </H4>
<F P=102> AU1002100894 Hamburg DPA in German 0914 GMT 10 Feb 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU1002100894 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Bonn (DPA) -- Chancellor Helmut Kohl and U.S. 
President Bill Clinton held an extensive telephone conversation 
last night to discuss the two countries' policy in Bosnia. As 
government spokesman Dieter Vogel reported in Bonn, Kohl 
emphatically supported the U.S. position, which is largely 
identical with French ideas. After the NATO decision Clinton 
warned the Bosnian Serbs and others against continuing to shell 
Bosnia's capital. Everyone who violates the decision, which is 
also largely based on U.S. proposals, "must be prepared for the 
consequences," Clinton said. The conflict itself "must be 
solved by the parties involved at the negotiating table," 
whereby the United States will take over a more substantial role. 
  According to Minister of the Chancellery Friedrich Bohl, the 
FRG has a "decisive share in the implementation of the ultimatum 
to Bosnia." On the ARD "Morgenmagazin" program, he explained 
that "behind the scenes and via diplomatic channels we made 
great efforts to come to this result." The minister of the 
chancellery does not see any parallels with the situation that 
led to World War I. In contrast with 1914, the international 
community this time is in complete agreement. The threat must 
be upheld at all costs, however. Germany must "provide moral and 
political support." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

