<F P=101> International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   France Says `No Half-Measures' on Bosnian Conflict </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BR0902150794 Rome ANSAMAIL Database in English 1409 GMT 9 
Feb 94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR0902150794 </F>
<F P=104>  Rome ANSAMAIL Database </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "Bosnia: U.S., France Pushing for </F>
NATO Ultimatum"] 
  [Text] Brussels, 9 Feb (ANSA) -- United States and French 
ambassadors to NATO were leading efforts today to overcome their 
Canadian and Greek colleagues' concern over an ultimatum to 
Bosnian Serbs to lift their siege of Bosnian capital Sarajevo, 
French sources reported. "Either there will be a decision 
today, or there will be none. There will be no half-measures," 
the French sources said during a break in the Atlantic Council 
to allow the 16 ambassadors to consult their governments. 
  According to the sources, the U.S.-French ultimatum proposal 
made this morning would give the forces which have been 
bombarding Sarajevo for 22 months 7-10 days to withdraw their 
heavy artillery to 20-30 kilometres from the perimeter of the 
city, or else face air strikes. Most NATO countries have 
expressed support for an ultimatum in response to the worst 
single civilian atrocity of the Bosnian war: the mortar shell 
that killed 68 and wounded over 200 in a Sarajevo market on 
Saturday [5 February]. 
  But Canada is particularly concerned about the possible 
repercussions on its large peacekeeping contingent, encircled at 
Srebrenica, in the wake of Bosnian Serb leader Radovan 
Karadzic's threat that "no foreigner will be safe" if air 
strikes are ordered. Greece fears that an escalation of the 
Bosnian war would dangerously raise tensions in Kosovo and the 
rest of the Balkan area. 
  The Council is meeting to respond to United Nations 
Secretary 
General Butrus Butrus-Ghali's call for a NATO green light on 
threatened air strikes to halt the massacre of Sarajevo 
civilians. If the Council approves the ultimatum, the last word 
as regards launching the strikes lies with Butrus-Ghali. 
  (In Moscow, the Interfax news agency reported that Russian 
Foreign Minister Andrey Kozyrev had written to Butrus-Ghali 
warning of the "extremely serious" consequences of "any air 
strike, even limited to providing air cover" for UN forces. 
Kozyrev was quoted as saying that air strikes "would jeopardise 
the entire UN aid operation." Stressing the priority of a 
political solution to the Bosnian crisis, he reiterated Russia's 
view that before ordering strikes Butrus-Ghali must consult with 
the UN Security Council, where Russia has indicated it will veto 
such a move.) 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

