<H3> <TI>   Notes Russian Stand on Bosnia </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BR1002092894 Rome ANSAMAIL Database in English 2231 GMT 9 
Feb 94 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR1002092894 </F>
<F P=104>  Rome ANSAMAIL Database </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "Bosnia: Andreatta on Russian </F>
Stance, Meets Silajdzic"] 
  [Text] Geneva, 9 Feb (ANSA) -- Russia's firm stance against 
NATO air strikes in Bosnia has changed, as Moscow realises that 
such a move would be "aimed at getting positive results," 
Italy's Foreign Minister Beniamino Andreatta said Wednesday [9 
February]. 
  Speaking after a meeting with Bosnian Premier Haris 
Silajdzic, where Russia's Deputy Foreign Minister Vitaliy 
Churkin was also present, Andreatta said "my impression was that 
the tension which has risen over the past few days has now 
subsided a lot, and that the Russians realise that NATO action 
(in Bosnia) would be aimed at getting positive results." 
  "It is not our job to use weapons simply for the sake of 
using weapons," Andreatta told the press. "They must be used as 
a political tool for achieving a certain solution. If, as it 
seems, heavy weapons are to be withdrawn, this has already been 
achieved and in this case arms will not be used or will be used 
only where heavy weapons remain in place." 
  The Italian diplomatic chief was referring to a UN-brokered 
ceasefire agreement reached Wednesday afternoon between Bosnian 
Serb and Moslem forces. 
  Andreatta described his talks with Siladjzic as "long and 
complex", with the Bosnian premier offering a view of peaceful 
co-existence between Moslems and Croats "which differed from 
that of peace negotiators and which had both interesting and 
problematic aspects which will have to be studied further." 

</TEXT>

