<F P=101> Netherlands </F>
<H3> <TI>   Dutch Air Force Trains for Attacks on Bosnia </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BR1002123994 The Hague ANP in Dutch 1540 GMT 9 Feb 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR1002123994 </F>
<F P=104>  The Hague ANP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Dutch </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Article signed SDC: "Netherlands Air Force Trains for </F>
Attacks on Bosnia"; as released by The Hague ANP Database] 
  [Text] The Hague, 9 Feb (ANP) -- F-16 pilots from the 
Netherlands Air Force are to begin exercises -- with real bombs 
-- on Monday [7 February] on the island of Vlieland for two 
weeks. The pilots will soon be serving over Bosnia. 
  During the exercises, the pilots will drop a total of 30 
500- 
pound bombs. Beginning on 1 April the pilots will be flying out 
of the Villafranca base in Italy for missions over Bosnia. 
  The NATO operation over Bosnia is intended to maintain the 
no- fly zone over the war zone by giving air support to the UN 
ground troops and, perhaps, by carrying out air strikes. These 
kinds of offensive actions will be the subject of in-depth talks 
today and Wednesday within NATO as a means of breaking the siege 
of Sarajevo. 
  Regular exercises with real bombs are very controversial for 
the population of the islands of Vlieland and Texel due to the 
noise and damage to the environment and houses. For that 
reason, the Defense Ministry has decided that the exercises will 
be restricted to just half an hour twice a day and not at all on 
the weekends. On both islands there are measuring posts for 
establishing the noise and vibrations caused by the explosions. 
If there is demonstrable damage then the exercise is suspended. 
The same also happens if weather conditions are unfavorable. 

</TEXT>

