<F P=100> INTER-EUROPEAN AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   States Neighboring Ex-Yugoslavia Meet in Geneva </TI></H3>
<H4>   Italy Concerned Over `Dominant' Power </H4>
<F P=102> LD1002004794 Rome RAI Uno Television Network in Italian 2330 
GMT 9 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1002004794 </F>
<F P=104>  Rome RAI Uno Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Italian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpt] In Geneva, the foreign ministers of the seven 
countries bordering the former Yugoslavia discussed for five 
hours the international consequences of the sanctions against 
Serbia and Montenegro and the most suitable way to prepare the 
rebuilding of the Balkans -- all this while the war is still 
raging. Some of those taking part spoke about the climate of 
the day's meeting. Foreign Minister Andreatta: 
  [Begin Andreatta recording] We discussed the rebuilding of a 
Balkan order. Even though our overall reading of the Yugoslav 
affair was not in perfect alignment, our chief cause for 
concern, which we all shared, was the possible creation of a 
dominant military power. [end recording] [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

