<H3> <TI>   PS, PSC To Discuss Amnesty for WWII Collaborationists </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BR0902144594 Groot-Bijgaarden DE STANDAARD in Dutch 8 Feb 94 
p 1 </F>

<F P=103> BR0902144594 </F>
<F P=104>  Groot-Bijgaarden DE STANDAARD </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Dutch </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Article signed GF: "PS and PSC Willing To Discuss Amnesty"] </F>
  [Text] Brussels -- The PS [Socialist Party] and PSC [Social 
Christian Party] are willing to have a discussion on amnesty. 
Yesterday, the party executives of both French-speaking parties 
unanimously approved a statement to that effect. The word 
amnesty is not pronounced, but during a press conference after 
the weekly meeting of the PS party executive, PS Chairman 
Philippe Busquin used the word without any hesitation. This had 
never happened before within the PS. The PSC is willing "to 
examine the family consequences of the postwar measures case by 
case." 
  The PS party executive subscribed to the words of Arthur 
Haulot, "the conscience of the resistance to fascism." In an 
appeal published in LE SOIR, Arthur Haulot stated he was no 
longer opposed to a "case by case investigation of those who ask 
for compassion," in a spirit of peace on the occasion of the 
fiftieth anniversary of our Liberation. As a resistance 
fighter, Haulot was arrested by the Gestapo in 1941, and 
survived three and one-half years at the concentration camps of 
Mauthausen and Dachau. By referring to the very old Haulot to 
tone down its implacable position on amnesty, the PS secures 
itself the best possible guarantee against protests by its rank 
and file. 
  The PS statement says that "social consequences for the 
relatives of the condemned people can be seriously examined case 
by case." This sentence is very similar to that of the PSC text. 
  In the PS' and PSC's view, amnesty is rejected for 
collaboration with the enemy, and only applies to the social and 
family consequences of collaboration. 
  The PS also emphasizes that it continues to be committed to 
"the democratic values." Busquin explained that after the 
elections, the PS will not form any coalitions with 
ultra-rightwing parties. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-38997 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drweu028_b_94003" </HT>


