<F P=100> UNITED KINGDOM </F>
<H3> <TI>   Aide Admits Malaysian Arms-And-Aid Deal `Was Agreed' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PM0902161894 London THE DAILY TELEGRAPH in English 9 Feb 94 
p 2 </F>

<F P=103> PM0902161894 </F>
<F P=104>  London THE DAILY TELEGRAPH </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Phillip Johnston, political correspondent: </F>
"Pergau Arms And Aid Link `Was Agreed'"] 
  [Text] A link between arms sales and aid granted to 
Malaysia for the controversial Pergau Dam project was agreed 
then dropped, the Government disclosed for the first time last 
night. 
  Mr Alastair Goodlad, Foreign Office Minister, said an 
agreement signed in 1988 contained a formula for a set 
percentage of the money spent on British military equipment to 
be reimbursed in aid. 
  In a Commons written question, Mr Alan Williams, Labour MP 
for Swansea West, asked whether the 1988 protocol "contained 
figures relating amounts or percentages of civil aid to amounts 
of arms purchases." 
  Mr Goodlad replied: "Yes." But he added that a letter was 
later sent by Mr George Younger, then Defence Secretary, to say 
aid could not be linked to defence sales. 
  "As a result, the issue was not taken up in the memorandum 
of 
understanding on defence procurement signed in September that 
year," Mr Goodlad explained. 
  However, the answer will bring renewed questions over 
ministerial assurances that no links existed between the aid 
package and arms -- something that could be challenged in law. 
  Mr Major and Mr Hurd, Foreign Secretary, overruled official 
advice to clear the 234 million pound aid, which has been 
described by MPs as a waste of money. Around the same time, a 
1.3 billion pound defence contract was negotiated with Malaysia. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

