<F P=100> FRANCE </F>
<H3> <TI>   Juppe Reasserts Commitment to NATO Plan for Bosnia </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1002134694 Paris France-2 Television Network in French 
1200 GMT 10 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1002134694 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris France-2 Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> French </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Concerning the NATO ultimatum to Bosnia, France 
played a leadership role. It succeeded in getting the United 
States, and finally all the NATO members, to follow in its wake. 
This morning Alain Juppe, the French minister of foreign 
affairs, repeated that it is essential to find a diplomatic 
solution to the matter. But most of all he repeated France's 
determination. Here he is: 
  [Begin Juppe recording] We are told that there has been a 
cease-fire agreement, and an agreement to withdraw heavy 
weapons. Fine. Let it be implemented in 10 days' time. If it 
is implemented 10 days from now, there won't be any problem. 
But there must be a signed agreement. An umpteenth cease-fire 
is not enough. 
  If we really want to stop the carnage, a cease-fire is not 
enough. The weapons which could at some time make it possible 
to start again have to be withdrawn. 
  France, which has the biggest contingent on the ground -- 
2,000 troops in Sarajevo -- was the one who made the proposal. 
This means we have faced up to our responsibilities, not 
without much deep thought, not without taking every possible 
precaution, of course, to bring together our men and to protect 
them as much as possible, but fully realizing that no protection 
plan can be 100 percent effective in such a situation, as 
Francois Leotard said here with me last Sunday. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

