<F P=100> FRANCE </F>
<H3> <TI>   Protest Held Against Ethnic Cleansing in Bosnia </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1002082594 Paris AFP in English 0241 GMT 10 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1002082594 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Strasbourg, Feb 10 (AFP) -- Two hundred crosses and 
tombstones symbolising the 200,000 people killed in the Bosnian 
conflict were planted Wednesday [9 February] on the lawns in 
front of the European Parliament building here. 
  About 1,200 people gathered in silence in front of the 
building to protest against ethnic cleansing, while some also 
called for military intervention in the conflict. 
  The crosses and tombstones were due to be removed during the 
night, despite protestors' hopes that they would be left in 
place for a few days as a reminder that all the green spaces in 
Sarajevo have been turned into cemeteries. 
  The organisers from a Strasbourg-based group say they intend 
to mount similar protests "until peace returns to Bosnia". 

</TEXT>

