<F P=100> FRANCE </F>
<H3> <TI>   Rocard `Would Lose Hands Down' in Presidential Elections </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1002131994 Paris AFP in English 1259 GMT 10 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1002131994 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Paris, Feb 10 (AFP) -- Opposition socialist leader 
Michel Rocard would lose hands down in French presidential 
elections against either of the two main rightwing contenders, 
Prime Minister Edouard Balladur and Gaullist leader Jacques 
Chirac, an opinion poll said Thursday [10 February]. 
  In the second round of presidential elections, which are due 
in May, 1995, Rocard would score 42 percent against 58 percent 
for Balladur, said the Louis Harris poll for the weekly VALEURS 
ACTUELLES. But Rocard improved his score by four points on a 
similar poll carried out a month ago while Balladur lost four 
points. 
  If the contest was with Chirac, Rocard would win 44 percent 
of the vote against 56 percent for Chirac, the poll said. The 
figures were identical to last month's. 

</TEXT>

