<F P=100> GREECE </F>
<H3> <TI>   Spokesman Views Possible Recognition of Macedonia </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC0902182594 Athens ATHENS NEWS in English 9 Feb 94 p 3 </F>
<F P=103> NC0902182594 </F>
<F P=104>  Athens ATHENS NEWS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpts] Athens yesterday had no choice but to 
reluctantly acknowledge receipt of U.S. advance notice that 
Washington would soon announce the diplomatic recognition of 
Skopje by the name of Former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia 
(FYROM). 
  "A new U.S. position on the recognition of Skopje is 
imminent," government spokesman Evangelos Venizelos told 
reporters in the press room. He was referring to an earlier 
meeting between Deputy Foreign Minister Yeoryios Papandreou and 
US Ambassador to Greece Thomas Niles. [passage omitted] 
  Mr Venizelos was reluctant to express Greek annoyance over 
the US move, but refused to offer easy excuses: "The American 
side has been preoccupied with this issue and has laboured over 
its own position on it for some time now, precisely because it 
takes into account the Greek stance. Up to a point, Washington 
understands -- or that's how we would like to interpret its 
stance so far -- that pressure has to be exercised on Skopje, 
because that's where the knotty problem lies, namely, how to 
bend the intransigence, the provocative attitude and the 
pseudo-irredentism of Skopje." Nevertheless, he finally admitted 
there would shortly be "an announcement of Skopje's recognition 
by the U.S." 
  Asked whether the government considered revising its 
"deterrent" diplomatic strategy after seemingly having lost its 
last trump card (which was the erstwhile U.S. reluctance to 
recognise Skopje) Mr Venizelos stopped short of admitting there 
was no other alternative. "Deterrence is not a wish, but the 
outcome of a determinate balance of international forces, which 
is beyond the power of any single country to influence on its 
own. However, a deterrent policy implies above all that we as a 
country have accurately defined our objectives. And this is 
what the government has done, reflecting a popular majority 
which transcends the electoral appeal of the (ruling) PASOK 
party." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

