<F P=100> GREECE </F>
<H3> <TI>   Spokesman, Others on U.S. Recognition of Macedonia </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC1002000794 Athens ET-1 Television Network in Greek 2130 
GMT 9 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC1002000794 </F>
<F P=104>  Athens ET-1 Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Greek </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpts] The United States today officially recognized 
the Former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia [FYROM] and said it 
will establish full diplomatic relations with it. A statement 
issued by the White House notes that the decision was made in 
recognition of the democratic expression by FYROM of the duty to 
establish a sovereign and independent state based on democratic 
principles. The full recognition was announced today but full 
diplomatic relations will be established when Skopje gives 
assurances that it will cooperate constructively for the 
settlement of its dispute with Greece, a U.S. ally for many 
years, as the statement points out. [passage omitted] 
  Skopje President Kiro Gligorov, who constantly refers to his 
country as the Republic of Macedonia, said that its independence 
and stability are a prerequisite for peace and stability in the 
Balkans. He also noted that good-neighborliness is a vital 
interest of his country and that Skopje is prepared to begin 
immediately to negotiate with Greece within the UN framework in 
goodwill and a desire for mutual understanding and respect for 
mutual interests. He also said that his country respects the 
territorial integrity and borders of Greece and of all the 
neighboring countries. 
  In Athens, Prime Minister Andreas Papandreou tonight 
received 
U.S. Ambassador to Greece Thomas Niles, who conveyed to him an 
official invitation from President Bill Clinton to visit the 
United States in April. 
  On the U.S. recognition of Skopje, government spokesman 
Evangelos Venizelos made the following statement: The Greek 
Government expresses its discontent at the U.S. decision to 
recognize Skopje. This development is certainly not pleasant for 
Greece. It is a wrong move by the United States. However, it 
is a significant fact that the United States is specifically 
reserved about diplomatic relations with Skopje and links it 
with conditions that refer to Skopje's hostile propaganda 
against Greece and to a respect for human rights. [passage 
omitted] 
  There has also been strong reaction by the opposition. New 
Democracy chairman Miltiadhis Evert described the U.S. decision 
as a bad option and added that the Greek Government was taken by 
surprise and was confused. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

