<F P=100> GERMANY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Minister Views Effect of NATO's Bosnia Decisions </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1002093694 Berlin DDP/ADN in German 0659 GMT 10 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1002093694 </F>
<F P=104>  Berlin DDP/ADN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Cologne (DDP/ADN) -- Chancellery Minister Friedrich 
Bohl is relying on the pressure put on the Serbs through the 
latest decisions by NATO ambassadors to have an effect. He 
expressed the hope that this will make it possible to implement 
the European Union peace plan, Bohl said on ARD TV's morning 
news program today. Peace will otherwise have to be brought 
about through military means. Bonn has actively worked for a 
unified NATO position "behind the scenes," he stated. 
  The Federal Republic cannot itself participate in military 
actions for historical and constitutional reasons, but will give 
the decisions made in Brussels its full "political and moral 
support," he said. Bohl rejected the idea that Europe would be 
on the brink of war after possible air strikes against artillery 
positions in Sarajevo. To draw parallels between 1914 and 1994 
is "false" and does not take into account the completely 
different situation now, he asserted. 

</TEXT>

