<F P=100> CYPRUS </F>
<H3> <TI>   UN's Feissel Meets Kliridhis; Talks Agenda Finalized </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC1002091094 Nicosia Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation Radio 
Network in Greek 0800 GMT 10 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC1002091094 </F>
<F P=104>  Nicosia Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation Radio 
Network </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Greek </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Gustave Feissel, the UN secretary general's 
alternate special representative in Cyprus, today had a new 
meeting with President Glavkos Kliridhis within the framework of 
negotiations to prepare the proximity talks on the 
confidence-building measures [CBM's]. 
  Entering the Presidential Palace, Feissel said things are 
proceeding normally, adding that he does not expect any 
difficulties. The goal of the UN official's meetings is to 
prepare an agenda and determine the points that each side 
considers crucial in implementing the CBM's. 
  According to the Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation's [CyBC] 
information, Kliridhis said the key-points are access to 
Famagusta's fenced-off area, the safety of the Greek Cypriots 
who will return to their homes in that area, and the travel 
documents that Turkish Cypriots will use at Nicosia Airport if 
and when it reopens. 
  Foreign Minister Alekos Mikhailidhis, government spokesman 
Ioannis Kasoulidhis, Deputy Minister to the President Pandelis 
Kouros, and UN political adviser John Paul Kavanagh participated 
in the meeting. Feissel will have another meeting with Turkish 
Cypriot leader Rauf Denktas tomorrow. He also met Denktas 
yesterday. 
  Leaving the Presidential Palace a short time ago, Feissel 
said the agenda of the proximity talks has been finalized, 
adding that it contains six topics. The UN envoy said he will 
inform the UN secretary general that the two sides have agreed 
on the agenda. He added that the proximity talks will begin on 
17 February, as scheduled. 
  Feissel confirmed a CyBC report braodcast yesterday that Joe 
Clark, the UN secretary general's special representative in 
Cyprus, will arrive in Cyprus next Tuesday [15 February] and 
will not be accompanied by UN experts. 

</TEXT>

