<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Possibility for Renewed U.S.-EU Audiovisual Dialogue </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BR0402154694 Brussels L'ECHO in French 4 Feb 94 p 3 </F>
<F P=103> BR0402154694 </F>
<F P=104>  Brussels L'ECHO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> French </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report: "Audiovisual: European Union-U.S. </F>
Dialogue Reopened Soon"] 
  [Text] After adopting a tougher tone at the beginning of 
January, the United States now seems to be ready for dialogue 
with the European Union (EU) on the audiovisual issue. 
  "This is very important for our country," Joan Spero, U.S. 
undersecretary of state for the economy, said on Thursday [3 
February] after discussions with her French and European 
Commission colleagues. "At the same time, we would like to find 
a means of establishing a somewhat calmer dialogue." 
  Top U.S. and European officials met this week in the 
framework of the "transatlantic declaration" which, since the 
end of the 1980's, has enabled Washington and Brussels to 
discuss their differences every six months instead of launching 
trade wars. The audiovisual sphere is still a considerable bone 
of contention, and U.S. Trade Representative Mickey Kantor 
stepped up the pressure in January, announcing an offensive 
against European aid systems, which he regards as discriminatory. 
  The end of the GATT negotiations in December did not make it 
possible to clear up the matter. The audiovisual sector is 
mentioned in the agreement, although the EU has not given any 
pledge to reduce its subsidies to the producers of programs or 
to dismantle legislation such as the quotas for the distribution 
of European works. For the Europeans, and especially France, 
this amounts to the "cultural exception" which had been demanded. 
  "As far as we are concerned, the matter is settled," a 
Commission spokesman said. But Washington does not see things 
that way and has not given up trying to force the opening up of 
European borders to products of its audiovisual industry, which 
generate export revenue of over $3.5 billion per year. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

