<F P=100> UNITED KINGDOM </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Leaders React To NATO Decision on Bosnia </TI></H3>
<H4>   Major Assures Moscow </H4>
<F P=102> LD1002195694 London PRESS ASSOCIATION in English 1922 GMT 10 
Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1002195694 </F>
<F P=104>  London PRESS ASSOCIATION </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By Sarah Womack, PRESS ASSOCIATION lobby correspondent] </F>
  [Text] The Prime Minister tonight set out to reassure 
Moscow that Russia and NATO shared the same aims on Bosnia. 
John Major, who leaves Britain for Russia on Monday [14 
February] for talks with President Boris Yeltsin, said: 
"Emphatically what NATO is doing is not taking sides in the 
conflict." 
  His remarks, in an interview for Russian television, came 
after Russia called for an emergency meeting of the UN Security 
Council to discuss the crisis in Bosnia following NATO's 
ultimatum to Serb forces around Sarajevo to withdraw their 
artillery within 10 days. 
  Mr Major said: "The objectives that the Russian government 
have are the same objectives that we have in the West. We would 
like to see the fighting stop, we would like to see a political 
settlement. 
  "Emphatically what NATO is doing is not taking sides in the 
conflict. That is not what we are doing. What we are concerned 
about is to stop the fighting around Sarajevo and the needless 
and ceaseless deaths that occur there. That is the purpose of 
what we are seeking to do. But the objective I believe is one 
that Russia shares -- and that is to find a negotiated 
settlement to this conflict. 
  "There is no other satisfactory ending." 
  Mr Major made his remarks shortly after he held brief talks 
at Downing Street with Russia's ambassador to London, Boris 
Pankin. 
  Earlier today, Russia's Foreign Ministry spokesman Grigoriy 
Karasin, in a mildly-worded statement, called for a negotiated 
end of the siege in the Bosnian capital. He told a briefing in 
Moscow that the Russian Federation proposed the convening of an 
immediate Security Council session to examine practical ways of 
demilitarising Sarajevo and introducing direct rule by the UN. 
His comments contrasted sharply with those earlier of Russian 
deputy foreign minister Anatoliy Adamishin. 
  Interfax quoted Adamishin as denouncing outright NATO's 
ultimatum to Bosnian Serb forces to withdraw artillery from 
Sarajevo in 10 days or face possible air strikes. 
  "Why should NATO make decisions on a (Bosnian) settlement, 
especially by way of ultimatums and threats to use force? This 
is not NATO's business. It is the job of the UN." 
  A UN Security Council session would bring what is for Russia 
a highly sensitive issue under the direct auspices of a body in 
which it enjoys a trump card -- a powerful veto right. 
  Karasin avoided any comments on Moscow's possible line at a 
Security Council meeting, should it be called. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

