<F P=100> UNITED KINGDOM </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Leaders React To NATO Decision on Bosnia </TI></H3>
<H4>   Rifkind Understands Russian Concern </H4>
<F P=102> LD1302154794 London PRESS ASSOCIATION in English 1429 GMT 13 
Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1302154794 </F>
<F P=104>  London PRESS ASSOCIATION </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By John Clark, PRESS ASSOCIATION] </F>
  [Text] Defence Secretary Malcolm Rifkind said today that 
Russian concern about possible airstrikes against Serbian 
positions around Sarajevo was "perfectly understandable." 
  Mr Rifkind's comments came ahead of the Prime Minister's 
visit to Moscow on Tuesday [15 February] when Mr Major is 
expected to discuss the Bosnian situation with Russian leader Mr 
Yeltsin. 
  The Defence Secretary, speaking in Edinburgh, said: "The 
Russian government has of course been very supportive of the UN 
and supported the Security Council resolution last year under 
which the possibility of air strikes is being organised. 
  "It's perfectly understandable there should be some concern. 
Everybody is concerned about the use of force." 
  Mr Rifkind emphasised his confidence in Lieutenant General 
Sir Michael Rose, the UN force commander who is seeking to 
implement the ceasefire. He also said that the role of UN 
commanders on the ground would be extremely important in any 
decision to launch air strikes because of the risk to UN forces 
and aid workers. 
  It was not unusual that there were differing degrees of 
support for international action, he added. 
  The important point was that the Security Council took a 
decision some months ago and the latest resolution on air 
strikes was based on that. 
  "In any account I am sure the views of all the nations 
concerned will continue to be considered," said Mr Rifkind. 
  The Defence Secretary was guest of honour at the official 
opening of a new 1 million pound headquarters of the Scottish 
Yeomanry, a new Territorial Army unit created 15 months ago for 
the role of light reconnaisance and home defence. 

</TEXT>

