<F P=100> UNITED KINGDOM </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Leaders React To NATO Decision on Bosnia </TI></H3>
<H4>   UK Suspends Aid Convoys </H4>
<F P=102> LD1002170394 London PRESS ASSOCIATION in English 1617 GMT 10 
Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1002170394 </F>
<F P=104>  London PRESS ASSOCIATION </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By Chris Moncrieff and Sarah Womack, PRESS ASSOCIATION </F>
political staff] 
  [Text] Britain has suspended aid convoys in Bosnia in the 
run-up to the deadline when the Serbs may face air strikes, 
Government officials said today. Officials said the British 
Government, in consultation with the United Nations High 
Commission for Refugees, had halted the convoys as a "prudent 
precaution." 
  They said: "We suspended our aid convoys and we gave advice 
and assistance to aid workers to make sure that they made their 
way to safe locations against the possibility that they might 
find themselves in danger." 
  The suspension took place from Monday and the decision was 
taken as part of contingency arrangements for the safety of aid 
workers delivering supplies. 
  Officials said: "With any luck we shall be able to start 
them 
again as we have in the past." 
  But they refused to speculate on the role now of British 
troops in Bosnia, who are there to provide protection escort to 
the humanitarian operation. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

