<F P=100> UNITED KINGDOM </F>
<H3> <TI>   Rocket Attack Damages Sinn Fein Headquarters </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1202124694 London PRESS ASSOCIATION in English 1222 GMT 12 
Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1202124694 </F>
<F P=104>  London PRESS ASSOCIATION </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By Ian Graham, PRESS ASSOCIATION correspondent] </F>
  [Excerpt] The Belfast headquarters of the IRA's political 
wing Sinn Fein was damaged in a rocket attack today. Local 
people said a rocket was fired from a car parked across the 
street from Connelly House in the Andersonstown Road. 
  Sinn Fein said the missile went through an upstairs window 
and exploded in an office, parts of the warhead imbedding 
themselves in a wall. No-one was in the building at the time, 
but a Sinn Fein spokesman said a meeting of party members had 
been due to start there soon afterwards. 
  Last Monday [7 February] a booby-trapped grenade planted by 
the loyalist Ulster Freedom Fighters was defused at the security 
gate outside the building. Sinn Fein President Gerry Adams 
visited the scene soon after the attack and accused the security 
forces of collusion in today's attack and others on Sinn Fein 
members in recent years. 
  "Loyalist death squads are operating with a high degree of 
intelligence information on individuals, offices and the 
movement of Crown forces patrols," he said. He insisted Sinn 
Fein would not be intimidated or deterred by the attacks from 
its search for peace. He claimed recent attacks were carried out 
with weapons provided to loyalists by British intelligence. 
[passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

