<H3> <TI>   Government Agrees With NATO Ultimatum on Bosnia </TI></H3>
<H4>   Clinton Assures Chretien </H4>
<F P=102> LD1002171094 Montreal Radio Canada International in English 
1430 GMT 10 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1002171094 </F>
<F P=104>  Montreal Radio Canada International </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] [Announcer] Yesterday NATO members agreed on a plan 
to bomb Bosnian Serb targets unless Serbs withdraw heavy weapons 
from around Sarajevo or place them under UN control within 10 
days. The Canadian Government had opposed air strikes, out of 
concern for the safety of its 800 peacekeepers on the ground in 
Bosnia. But Prime Minister Jean Chretien said Canada had 
changed its position, in order to protect the civilian 
population in Sarajevo. 
  [Begin recording] [Chretien] The Bosnian Serbs have accepted 
to see the Canadians replaced by the Dutch before the end of 
this month. So, the situation is progressing normally there, 
and according to the news that I've heard a few minutes ago the 
Serbs have agreed to accept the ultimatum in relation to 
Sarajevo. So there will be no need for air strikes, but indeed 
we are [as heard] accepted, in order to protect the civilians in 
Sarajevo and not to see the repetition of the massacre of the 
last weekend. [end recording] 
  [Announcer] Canadian Prime Minister Jean Chretien. Canada's 
foreign affairs minister, Andre Ouellet, says a major factor in 
Ottawa's reversal against the air strikes was a promise by U.S. 
President Bill Clinton. He telephoned Prime Minister Chretien 
twice yesterday to give assurances that the U.S. will be very 
involved in the process to ensure a peaceful solution to the 
conflict. 

</TEXT>

