<F P=100> CANADA </F>
<H3> <TI>   ROK Foreign Minister Begins Official Visit </TI></H3>
<H4>   To Discuss NAFTA </H4>
<F P=102> SK1402010194 Seoul YONHAP in English 0046 GMT 14 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1402010194 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Ottawa, Feb. 13 (YONHAP) -- South Korean Foreign 
Minister Han Sung-chu began his visit to Canada on Sunday [13 
February] intending to cement ties with the member of the North 
American Free Trade Agreement (NAFTA). 
  He meets his Canadian counterpart Andre Ouellet on Monday 
and 
will propose ways to strengthen trade links between South Korea 
and NAFTA, including the establishment of "special cooperative 
relations," officials said. 
  They are to discuss post-Uruguay Round bilateral trade 
arrangements and regional cooperation through the Asia-Pacific 
Economic Cooperation (APEC) forum, the officials said. 
  Han meets Secretary of Commerce Roy MacLaren first and is 
expected to urge Canada to extend its general preferential 
tariff (GPT) status for South Korea that ends in June, as well 
as lower import and other trade barriers to South Korean 
products. 
  He will call on Prime Minister Jean Chretien on Tuesday 
before going to the United Nations, where he plans to confer 
with Secretary-General Butrus Butrus-Ghali on the North Korean 
nuclear problem and possible measures by the UN Security Council. 

</TEXT>

