<F P=100> CANADA </F>
<H3> <TI>   ROK Foreign Minister Begins Official Visit </TI></H3>
<H4>   Comments on DPRK Nuclear Policy </H4>
<F P=102> SK1402014394 Seoul YONHAP in English 0134 GMT 14 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1402014394 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpts] Ottawa, Feb. 13 (YONHAP) -- North Korea and the 
United States are likely to meet this week and may agree on 
International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) inspections, South 
Korean Foreign Minister Han Sung-chu said Sunday [13 February]. 
  In Canada on a tour of North American Free Trade Agreement 
(NAFTA) members, Han said he expects North Korea to come forward 
with a positive response soon. 
  "Chances are high that North Korea will reopen contact with 
the United States this week in New York and reveal its 
position," said Han. 
  Han's optimism follows a statement last Saturday by the 
North 
Korean Foreign Ministry spokesman claiming Washington has told 
Pyongyang it wants to solve the nuclear problem through dialogue 
and that North Korea also wants such a solution. 
  He called the statement "a meaningful change" on North 
Korea's part and predicted a meeting with the United States 
before the IAEA negotiations. 
  South Korean sources explained that North Korea and the 
United States have had opportunities to exchange views, although 
not in official surroundings like the New York contact. [passage 
omitted] 
  U.S. congressmen and the press have been pressing the 
administration to take punitive action against North Korea for 
refusing to submit to IAEA inspections. 
  Han, however, emphasized a diplomatic solution in his talks 
with U.S. officials last week. 
  Washington had left the inspection issue to be solved by 
North Korea and the IAEA, refusing to negotiate on behalf of the 
Agency or to meddle in details. 
  But the United States decided to reopen contact with North 
Korea this week at South Korea's urging for another try at a 
diplomatic solution, according to the sources. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

