<F P=100> GERMANY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Rexrodt Views `Stony Path of Structural Renewal' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0902152594 Duesseldorf HANDELSBLATT in German 9 Feb 94 p 3 </F>
<F P=103> AU0902152594 </F>
<F P=104>  Duesseldorf HANDELSBLATT </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report signed "uhl": "Rexrodt: Taboos Challenged for </F>
First Time"] 
  [Text] Bonn -- The views of what concrete actions have to 
be taken to secure the future of the German economy and society 
are converging. This opinion was expressed by Economics 
Minister Guenter Rexrodt, of the Free Democratic Party of 
Germany [FDP], at the beginning of the forum on safeguarding 
Germany as a business and investment location, which was 
sponsored by his ministry. 
  For the first time in decades, taboos are being challenged, 
intellectual inflexibility is easing, and bureaucratic 
ossification in industry and trade is being tackled. The main 
task is to get the discrepancy between costs and output under 
control and to improve the conditions for excellence in the 
spheres of education, science, technology, and development and 
their translation into successful products. 
  Apart from that, individual responsibility in the social 
sphere must increase and "work, which is abundant," must "lead 
to lasting employment." The struggle against unemployment is 
the government's most important goal. There are no patent 
prescriptions, "we must embark upon the stony path of structural 
renewal." 
  Uwe Jens, economic-policy spokesman for the Social 
Democratic 
Party of Germany [SPD] Bundestag group, however argued that 
"show events cannot replace competent economic policy." The 
repeated attacks against the foundations of the social market 
economy by the FDP and its economics minister are only intended 
to conceal the years of deficiencies regarding the strengthening 
of the growth forces and the economy's competitive strength. 
  Horst Koehler, the head of the Savings Banks Association, 
pleaded for a tax system that is more appropriate to promote 
hard work and the "purification" of state administration. The 
FRG will no longer be a net exporter of capital for an extended 
period of time. Hence, the confidence that was gained in 40 
years has to be "carefully cultivated." 
  The Federation of German Trade Unions [DGB] proposed a 
"five-path strategy." The "solid starting position" of German 
enterprises, for example in environmental, energy, and 
communications technology, as well as microelectronics or 
biotechnology must be further developed with the help of an 
"innovation impetus." In addition, the country needs an 
education and qualification offensive and employment initiative 
in terms of economic, industrial, and regional policy. 
  Active labor market policy must replace the financing of 
unemployment through the financing of socially sensible work. 
As for wage policy, the system of independent wage talks must 
be preserved, and area wage agreements must be geared toward 
modernizing branches and regions. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

