<F P=100> GERMANY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Rexrodt, Lafontaine Differ Over Labor Market </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1002170594 Berlin DIE WELT in German 10 Feb 94 p 11 </F>
<F P=103> AU1002170594 </F>
<F P=104>  Berlin DIE WELT </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [DIE WELT report: "Controversy Over Labor Market Policy"] </F>
  [Text] Bonn -- After the two-day business location forum, 
FRG Economics Minister Guenter Rexrodt has struck a positive 
balance in the talks and advocated a further dialogue between 
politicians, the economy, and trade unions. In the discussion, 
it was the majority's opinion that the present problems of the 
German economy cannot be overcome by an economic recovery alone. 
It is particularly important for him that it was no longer 
discussed "whether" deregulation, privatization, and the opening 
of the market are to be carried out "but how" this is to be 
done, Rexrodt said. 
  In the opinion of Michael Glos, chairman of the Christian 
Social Union [CSU] land group, the business location forum has 
proven that Bonn's policy with its 30-point action program is 
correct. It is now the turn of both sides of industry to 
contribute their share to more flexibility and efficiency 
regarding working hours and wage costs. 
  At the same time, the Social Democratic Party of Germany 
[SPD] sharply criticized the Bonn coalition. SPD Deputy 
Chairman Oskar Lafontaine reproached it for its "complete 
failure" in economic and financial policies. A comprehensive 
growth and employment concept has to be immediately developed. 
In return, Friedrich Bohl (Christian Democratic Union), 
minister in the Chancellor's Office, called on the Saarland 
minister president "to put the economic policy of his land in 
order first before he hands out advice to the government." Bohl 
advocated the promotion of more part-time work. In the 
Netherlands, 34 percent of all jobs are part time and in the 
FRG, it is only 17 percent, he said. 

</TEXT>

