<F P=100> ITALY &amp; VATICAN CITY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Napolitano, Butrus-Ghali Discuss Bosnia Situation </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1202143894 Rome RAI Uno Television Network in Italian 1230 
GMT 12 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1202143894 </F>
<F P=104>  Rome RAI Uno Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Italian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Giorgio Napolitano, the speaker of the Chamber of 
Deputies, has had talks in New York with UN Secretary General 
Butrus-Ghali about the situation in Bosnia following the NATO 
ultimatum. 
  Both men agreed that the NATO decision was a strong 
incentive 
to resume negotiations, thanks to the military and other 
pressure being applied to the Serbs. Nevertheless, Napolitano 
and Butrus-Ghali hoped that there would be no need for recourse 
to military intervention, and that the political will to find a 
solution to the conflict would prevail. 
  During his two-day visit to the United States, Napolitano 
has 
met congressmen and members of the Clinton administration as 
well as members of the Italian community and those from the 
world of economics and finance. 

</TEXT>

