<F P=100> ITALY &amp; VATICAN CITY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Political Parties React To Possible Bosnia Intervention </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BR1002131294 Rome LA REPUBBLICA in Italian 10 Feb 94 p 3 </F>
<F P=103> BR1002131294 </F>
<F P=104>  Rome LA REPUBBLICA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Italian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report: "Occhetto and Berlusconi Are in Favor </F>
of Intervention"] 
  [Text] Rome -- The war in Bosnia is leading to strange 
rapprochements. In fact, as regards the possibility of military 
intervention in former Yugoslavia, [Democratic Party of the 
Left] Secretary Occhetto has found himself holding a similar 
position to that of [Forza Italia leader] Berlusconi and the MSI 
[Italian Social Movement], whereas Communist Renewal has 
declared itself against armed intervention. Occhetto said he 
was in no doubt that "we must intervene in Bosnia, and the 
international community must take up an active position. We 
cannot be helpless bystanders in witnessing such an atrocious 
war." MSI Deputy Cristiana Muscardini also stated where her 
party stood on this matter: "We have had enough words, enough of 
war! We Italians, and all Europeans, have the duty to commit 
ourselves resolutely so as to achieve a solution to the Bosnian 
conflict." For Berlusconi, on the other hand, peacemaking 
actions in Bosnia must be backed by military force, and Italy 
must support, within the European Community, the "line of 
determination," making available "its prestige and its military 
bases" to this end. The only voice against armed intervention 
was that of Communist Renewal member Ersilia Salvato, who stated 
that her party was definitely against the use of force in former 
Yugoslavia. 

</TEXT>

