<F P=100> ITALY &amp; VATICAN CITY </F>
<H3> <TI>   `Sensational Development' in `Clean Hands' Reported </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1102140994 Rome RAI Due Television Network in Italian 1200 
GMT 11 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1102140994 </F>
<F P=104>  Rome RAI Due Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Italian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Let us begin with Paolo Berlusconi's arrest. Dario 
Carrella reports from Milan: 
  [Carrella] There was another sensational development this 
morning in the clean hands offensive. Another qualitative leap 
forward was made. 
  Paolo Berlusconi was arrested on the order of the Milan 
public prosecutor's office, which had made him the subject of a 
warrant for preventive detention. Examining Judge Italo Ghitti 
and Prosecuting Judge Antonio Di Pietro will question him this 
afternoon. 
  The arrest warrant is within the framework of investigations 
into kickbacks paid to encourage the Cariplo [Cassa Risparmio 
delle Provincie Lombarde] pensions fund to purchase several 
buildings. Berlusconi has been accused by one of those under 
investigation-- broker Giuseppe Clerici, who was formerly a 
Cariplo employee--of paying a bribe of more than 1 billion lire. 
News about Berlusconi's involvement in this chapter of the 
clean hands investigation has been making the rounds for several 
days. 
  The clean hands judges have also ordered two other arrests, 
but this time related to illegal financing of political parties. 
Giovanni Donigaglia, chairman of the Argenta building 
cooperative has been arrested. The Milan judiciary had already 
investigated Donigaglia within the framework of possible illegal 
contributions to the Italian Communist Party. This time 
Donigaglia is accused of having illegally paid 350 million lire 
to former Christian Democratic Party treasurer Severino 
Citaristi during the 1992 general election campaign. 
  Antonio Mosconi, former managing director of Toro 
Assicurazioni, part of the Fiat Group, has also been arrested. 
He is accused of having illegally given 200 million lire to 
Cesare De Piccoli, the former communist deputy mayor of Venice. 
The Milan public prosecutor's office has sent a cautionary 
warrant to De Piccoli, who is currently a PDS [Democratic Party 
of the Left] member of the European Parliament. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

