<F P=100> SPAIN </F>
<H3> <TI>   Gonzalez: `No Unilateral Withdrawal' From Bosnia </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1102151594 Madrid RNE-1 Radio Network in Spanish 1300 GMT 
11 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1102151594 </F>
<F P=104>  Madrid RNE-1 Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpts] [Prime Minister] Felipe Gonzalez has just 
concluded a one-hour news conference. We are going over to the 
Moncloa for a full report from Jose Luis Garcia del Pozo. 
  [Garcia del Pozo] [passage omitted] In conclusion, the prime 
minister spoke of Bosnia and of the situation of our troops 
engaged in humanitarian tasks there on the United Nation's 
behalf. He said that everything possible is being done to 
protect the men and that there will, of course, be no unilateral 
withdrawal. He said that, and I quote, we are not going to make 
a unilateral decision to withdraw our troops. We will talk to 
our partners because the effect of such a decision on our 
country's international credibility would be very negative. 
This would be linked to the fact that our country has already 
spent a long time (?enshrined)--as Gonzalez put it--in isolation 
from the international community. 

</TEXT>

