<F P=100> CYPRUS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Experts Prepare Documents on Talks </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC1302100894 Nicosia I SIMERINI in Greek 10 Feb 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> NC1302100894 </F>
<F P=104>  Nicosia I SIMERINI </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Greek </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Kostas Venizelos] </F>
  [Text] Government experts have prepared two documents on 
the confidence-building measures. Based on reliable I SIMERINI 
information, the first document, which contains suggestions and 
observations on specific aspects of the package, is at the 
foreign minister's office and the National Council members can 
pay a visit for a briefing. The second, nine-page document has 
been given to the National Council members in light of their 
scheduled meeting next Tuesday. 
  The confidential document entitled "Basic Principles and 
Positions on the Confidence-Building Measures" does not answer 
any concerns stemming from the UN proposals. Referring to the 
issue of recognition, the document points out that in order for 
there to be recognition of the pseudostate, our side must first 
give its consent. It goes on to suggest that our side reiterate 
its position that it does not intend to recognize the 
pseudostate is added at this point. The document refers 
extensively to passages from UN Secretary General Butrus 
Butrus-Ghali's report (July) and his recent letter to the two 
sides. 
  The document lists the following as our side's basic 
positions on the confidence-building measures: 
  First: Cyprus' sovereignty will be maintained and 
implementation will not contain elements of direct or indirect 
recognition. 
  Second: UN authority over Nicosia Airport and Varosha will 
be 
temporary and its orders will be in line with the international 
organization's resolutions. 
  Third: Settlement in these two areas is strictly temporary. 
  Fourth: Neither side will change positions. 
  Fifth: An agreement and implementation of the 
confidence-building measures does not imply a Cyprus solution. 
  The first document, which has not been given to the 
political 
leaders, is lengthy and in general describes the Greek Cypriot 
policy and approach on the talks. 
  The documents were prepared by a group of government experts 
(Triandafillidhis, Soulioti, and other officials) as well as 
Brownling and Aimiliou, who work in London. The three documents 
were sent to Brownling last May, when they were submitted to the 
sides, and he decided that there was no issue of recognition. 
The government then sought a second opinion from Greek 
specialists, who warned of the dangers. Following this 
development, a group of experts was formed to study the 
confidence-building measures in detail. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-39149 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drweu030_o_94004" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-WEU-94-030 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  14 Feb 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> CYPRUS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Denktas Intends To Use Reports </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC1302103894 Nicosia I MAKHI in Greek 10 Feb 94 pp 1, 7 </F>
<F P=103> NC1302103894 </F>
<F P=104>  Nicosia I MAKHI </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Greek </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] In an exclusive statement to the private television 
station ANTENNA, Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktas was 
explicit in his answers on the UN experts' reports. He insisted 
that although the reports are not part of the 
confidence-building measures package, they include promises made 
to the Turkish Cypriot side by the UN secretary general and UN 
experts on the benefits to the Turkish Cypriots when the 
measures are implemented. 
  He told ANTENNA: "Naturally, we will take whatever is 
included in the reports that will benefit the Turkish Cypriots. 
Nobody can tell us `Don't touch.' We will not throw away the 
reports. They include indications of what we can achieve 
through the confidence-building measures. 
  "The reason the people agreed to the talks is certainly 
related to what can be achieved. How can we say that the 
reports are invalid? Of course they exist and of course they 
are a tool that we will use." 
  The Turkish Cypriot leader said the reports were prepared by 
the experts to be used. "Otherwise, he said, there was no 
reason to prepare them." He continued: "If the reports were 
irrelevant, there was no reason to spend the experts' time and 
money on us. They have spent hours working with us. So, why do 
you, Greek Cypriots, avoid them? I do not understand." 
  Discussing the time frame for Nicosia Airport to reopen and 
Varosha's residents to return to the fenced off area, Denktas 
said this will depend on developments. He said: "Don't forget 
that the reports refer to 18 months for Nicosia Airport to 
reoperate and two to five years for Varosha." 
  Finally, the Turkish Cypriot leader said this week's 
meetings 
aim to prepare an agenda for the proximity talks which will 
begin on 17 February when Joe Clark, the UN secretary general's 
special representative in Cyprus, will be in Cyprus. Denktas 
said: "Clark will arrive in Cyprus on 17 February or a few days 
earlier, and will be with us for a few separate meetings. He 
will then leave us with Gustave Feissel." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

