<F P=100> TURKEY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government To Reinforce F-16's in Italy </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  TA1202152294 Ankara ANATOLIA in English 1450 GMT 12 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> TA1202152294 </F>
<F P=104>  Ankara ANATOLIA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Ankara, Feb 12 (A.A) -- Turkey on Saturday [12 
February] decided to reinforce its F-16 warplanes, which were 
stationed in Italy's Ghedi base, in a bid to control 
Bosnia-Herzegovina airspace. 
  Turkey said it took the decision after NATO's Southern 
European Allied Forces Commander Micheal Boord's call that an 
air operation will be launched against Serbia if it fails to 
withdraw its forces from Sarajevo in ten days. 
  The 16-membered NATO earlier agreed to order air strikes 
against Bosnian Serb forces besieging Sarajevo unless they 
withdraw artillery and other heavy weapons at least 20 km (12 
miles) or put them under U.N. control within 10 days. 
  General Staff spokesman Dogun Silahcioglu told an AA 
reporter 
that with the reinforcement Turkish Air Forces will have 18 F-16 
type warplanes in Ghedi base that will be ready for the air 
operation. 
  Meanwhile, AA learned that Greece did not give permission 
for 
the eight F-16 warplanes to pass through Greek airspace. 
  Officials said Turkish warplanes will pass to Ghedi base 
over 
the Mediterranean Sea on Feb 14. 

</TEXT>

