<F P=100> TURKEY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Azerbaijan President Aliyev Continues Visit </TI></H3>
<H4>   Report on Joint Communique </H4>
<F P=102> TA1102201094 Ankara TRT Television Network in Turkish 1800 
GMT 11 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> TA1102201094 </F>
<F P=104>  Ankara TRT Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Turkish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Announcer-read report over video] </F>
  [Text] Turkey and Azerbaijan have stated that the upper 
Karabakh region is an integral part of Azerbaijan, and called on 
Armenia to stop its attacks. Azerbaijani President Geydar 
Aliyev, concluding his official visit, left Turkey. 
  The joint communique on the visit states that during the 
meetings, which were conducted in a friendly, brotherly, and 
respectful atmosphere, views were exchanged on bilateral 
relations as well as regional and international issues. 
  Adamantly condemning the Armenian attacks on Azerbaijan, the 
communique further notes: During the meetings it was determined 
that more than 20 percent of Azerbaijani territory is occupied 
by Armenia; that more than 1 million Azeris are refugees in 
their own land; and that the United Nations is not implementing 
its Resolutions 822, 853, 874, and 884. Confirming once more 
that the upper Karabakh region is an integral part of 
Azerbaijan, both countries called on Armenia to stop its attacks 
on Azerbaijan. Turkey and Azerbaijan stated that Armenia is held 
accountable internationally for violating the peace and security 
in the region, and for forcefully standing against the 
international norms. 
  According to the communique, President Suleyman Demirel 
accepted an invitation from Aliyev to visit Azerbaijan. 

</TEXT>

