<F P=100> GREECE </F>
<H3> <TI>   Insists on `Need To Review' Policy </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC1202170394 Athens ELEVTHEROTIPIA in Greek 12 Feb 94 p 3 </F>
<F P=103> NC1202170394 </F>
<F P=104>  Athens ELEVTHEROTIPIA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Greek </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpts] The government yesterday issued its strongest 
warning to Skopje that "Greece's patience is running out." The 
warning was issued in case Skopje increases its provocations 
against Athens. 
  Following Prime Minister Andreas Papandreou's statement 
Thursday [10 February] night at the presidential palace 
regarding the end of dialogue with Skopje, the government 
spokesman yesterday spoke with equally strong language when he 
issued a harsh warning to Skopje. 
  The government reminded [Macedonian President Kiro] Gligorov 
that the recent international recognitions of his state do not 
diminish for Skopje the importance of normalizing relations with 
Greece at all. [passage omitted] 
  In this way, the government is attempting to send a message 
in "two directions:" 
  First, to the government of Skopje not to continue 
provocative statements or actions due to the "comfort" of the 
recent recognitions. 
  Second, to the international community to refrain from 
encouraging Skopje by taking further actions that would actually 
force the Greek Government to harden its stance toward Skopje. 
  Yesterday the government spokesman repeated that "there is 
no 
sense in a dialogue" if Skopje does not show specific and 
practical signs of satisfying the Greek conditions. 
  However, the government is not willing at this time to 
indicate what moves and measures it intends to take to pressure 
Skopje. 
  However, the government's policy in the diplomatic and 
economic fields is already under review and reform, but with no 
specific indications as to how it will move, except to say there 
is a "specific time limit" to its patience. 
  For his part, Deputy Foreign Minister Yeoryios Papandreou 
yesterday insisted on the need to review Greece's policy toward 
Skopje. Replying to criticism by the opposition regarding the 
dangers of ending the dialogue, he described the prime 
minister's statement in this regard as a "rhetorical phrase." 
[passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

