<F P=100> GREECE </F>
<H3> <TI>   Spokesman Reiterates Warning on Macedonia </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC1302175794 Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network in 
Greek 1600 GMT 13 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC1302175794 </F>
<F P=104>  Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Greek </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Greece is doing a lot more than it makes public on 
the Skopje issue, and this is a basic principle of its foreign 
policy. This statement was made today in Thessaloniki by 
Government Spokesman Evangelos Venizelos. Asked to comment on 
information regarding the increased U.S. presence in Skopje, 
Venizelos said: 
  [Begin recording] [Venizelos] I do not want to comment on 
this possibility. I would instead like to remind you of the 
government's basic statement of last Friday [11 February]: that 
there are limits to Greece's patience in awaiting practical 
indications that Skopje has accepted its conditions, and these 
limits are being reached. No one should underestimate this 
message, which has many addressees. 
  [Unidentified correspondent] Have there been any 
conciliatory signs from Skopje since the government's statement? 
  [Venizelos] There was a letter from [Macedonian President 
Kiro] Gligorov to U.S. President Bill Clinton on Friday -- 
Thursday night -- which had provocative contents for Greece. 
  [Correspondent] And the dialogue? 
  [Venizelos] The dialogue will depend on practical signs of 
Skopje accepting Greece's conditions. I repeat that Greece can 
only participate in a dialogue following specific and practical 
signs that Skopje has accepted its conditions. This position 
remains absolutely and firmly in effect. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

