<F P=100> GREECE </F>
<H3> <TI>   Thessaloniki Protests U.S. Recognition of Macedonia </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC1202092094 Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network in 
Greek 1800 GMT 11 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC1202092094 </F>
<F P=104>  Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Greek </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The Executive Committee of the Thessaloniki chapter 
of the Union of Municipalities and Communes of Greece today 
submitted a resolution to James Blanford, U.S. consul general in 
Thessaloniki, protesting the U.S. decision to recognize Skopje. 
Konstandinos Kosmopoulos, Thessaloniki mayor and committee 
president, headed the committee. Correspondent Dhespina Khari 
reports: 
  [Begin Khari recording] The resolution addressed to U.S. 
President Bill Clinton and the U.S. Administration stresses that 
this action is against the historical [word indistinct] of the 
symbols and boundaries of Greece, since they are threatened if 
this situation continues. Consequently, it also threatens to 
ignite the greater Balkan region. Finally, the resolution 
stresses that the current stance of the United States fatally 
injures the traditional friendship between the Greek and 
American people. It also creates an adverse climate for the 
United States from the Greeks who expected understanding and 
justice from our great ally. The resolution asks the United 
States to exert pressure on Skopje to eliminate all those 
aspects that obstruct the development of good relations with 
this state, including the name, symbols, propaganda, and 
expansionist designs. 
  In a statement, Kosmopoulos emphasized that this U.S. action 
has shaken Greece, called on the government to take a position 
on the issue, and noted that people and leadership should 
finally unite to face the critical issues of the country. 
  The mayors of Macedonian towns plan to hold an extraordinary 
meeting 19 February to decide on new initiatives in the 
framework of the local administrations and submit proposals to 
the Central Committee for dealing with the issue further. It 
has not been ruled out that they will propose new dynamic 
mobilization, similar to the rally of 14 February 1992 in 
Thessaloniki and the one in Athens in 1993. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

