<F P=100> GREECE </F>
<H3> <TI>   Opposition Leader Criticizes Macedonian Policy </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC1202205294 Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network in 
Greek 1800 GMT 12 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC1202205294 </F>
<F P=104>  Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Greek </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Miltiadhis Evert, New Democracy and official 
opposition leader, has returned from a long visit to European 
capitals and once again described the government's decision to 
cut off dialogue on the Skopje issue at the United Nations as a 
mistake. Correspondent Elli Triandafillou has the following 
report: 
  [Triandafillou] Speaking upon his return at the airport, 
Evert said he promoted the national positions during his 
contacts. He called on all Greek politicians to follow his 
example and visit foreign countries to help elevate the 
country's prestige, which, he claimed, is at a very low level. 
He also noted that his party's proposal for the signing of an 
agreement guaranteeing peace and unchanged borders in the 
Balkans is welcomed abroad. He added that the government should 
undertake an initiative to implement this because this way 
Turkey's expansionist plans in our region will be foiled. He 
also stressed that domestic disputes among political parties 
should not extend to foreign affairs and underlined that the 
Greek presidency of the European Union should succeed. 
  Referring to the developments on the Skopje issue, the 
official opposition leader repeated that the government made a 
mistake in abandoning the negotiations within the UN framework. 
Evert said that Deputy Foreign Minister Yeoryios Papandreou's 
clarification, that the prime minister's statement about ending 
the dialogue with neighboring Skopje was a "rhetorical 
statement" is ironic. 
  Responding to a question on remarks by Sotirios Kouvelas 
[New 
Democracy prominent deputy and former state minister] in which 
he criticized New Democracy's opposition policy, Evert said he 
will listen to all views, but made it clear that the final 
decisions are up to him. 
  Evert will go to Paris in February to meet with French Prime 
Minister Edouard Balladur. He also plans to meet German 
Chancellor Helmut Kohl and British Prime Minister John Major. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

