<F P=100> GREECE </F>
<H3> <TI>   Spokesman Defends Greek Stance on NATO Decision </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC1302202794 Athens ET-1 Television Network in Greek 1900 
GMT 13 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC1302202794 </F>
<F P=104>  Athens ET-1 Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Greek </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Belgian Foreign Minister Willy Claes said he will 
come to Athens on Thursday [17 February] in an effort to 
convince Greece to support NATO's threat of bombing raids 
against the Bosnian Serbs besieging Sarajevo. Claes told 
Belgian Television it is sad that Greece has the presidency of 
the European Union [EU], which is in danger of losing its 
credibility if our country is not convinced to give priority to 
the Yugoslav crisis during its term. 
  Replying to the Belgian foreign minister's statement, Greek 
Foreign Ministry Spokesman Konstandinos Bikas stressed that 
Greece has given top priority in its EU presidency to settling 
the Yugoslav crisis. And added: The Greek position is that 
issuing ultimatums to the involved parties in Sarajevo is not 
necessary and entails dangers of the spread of the crisis. This 
position is well-founded and we believe it will be justified by 
developments. 

</TEXT>

